<DESCRIPT>  SPORT; BRIEF  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Quarterback Todd Marinovich was suspended indefinitely from Southern Cal's
football team Friday, and Coach Larry Smith said the sophomore might not
return to the team.;    Smith announced his decision after Marinovich, who is
not registered for the spring semester, missed a mandatory team meeting.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  USC'S MARINOVICH HIT WITH SUSPENSION  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Sports Digest  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The suspension, the second for Marinovich this school year, followed by one
day a published report saying that Marinovich had decided to pass up his final
two seasons at USC to enter the 1991 NFL draft.;    "I've suspended Todd
indefinitely from our program," Smith said. "His scholarship to the university
is still intact, but he is not part of our football program in any way.";   
Marinovich is the No. 2 passer in USC history with 415 completions in two
seasons.; BASEBALL: Shortstop Shawon Dunston agreed to a $2.1 million,
one-year contract with the Chicago Cubs. Dunston, 27, batted .262 in 1990,
with 17 home runs and 66 RBIs. . . . First baseman Dave Magadan agreed to a
one-year contract with the New York Mets, tripling his salary to $1.25
million. Magadan was third in the National League in batting last season with
a .328  average.; SWIMMING: U.S. swimmers Matt Biondi and Jeff Rouse set meet
records in heats at the World Swimming Championships in Perth, Australia, and
Mike Barrowman lowered his world record in the men's 200-meter breaststroke.
Biondi, a former Cal standout, led qualifying for the men's 50 freestyle in
22.42 seconds --.07 seconds faster than the championship record set by
teammate Tom Jager in Madrid, Spain, in 1986. Jager, the world-record holder
in the event and a member of the Santa Clara Swim Club, was second in the heat
in 21.81. Rouse, the U.S.-record holder in the men's 100 backstroke, set a
meet mark in his heat at 55.34 seconds. Summer Sanders of Stanford led
qualifying for the women's 200 IM in 2:15.88. . . . A 15-member national team
from the Soviet Union has agreed to compete in the Santa Clara Invitational at
the Santa Clara International Swim Center on July 5-7, center head coach Jay
Fitzgerald said. Along with the Soviets and the United States, the meet also
has commitments from Australia, Japan, Canada, Mexico and New Zealand.;
COLLEGES: Stanford players Alex O'Brien and Jared Palmer won singles matches
to advance to the third round of the National Collegiate Tennis Championships
in Palm Desert. O'Brien posted a 6-2, 6-0 victory over Ashly Nauman of
Pepperdine, and Palmer beat Carl Chang of Cal 2-6, 6-2, 6-3. . . . New Mexico
is first, Stanford third and San Jose State fourth in the seven-team Spartan
Open men's gymnastics meet at SJS. Competition continues today.; MISCELLANY:
In Atlantic City, N.J., Ray Mercer knocked out Francesco Damiani with a left
uppercut late in the ninth round to become the World Boxing Organization
heavyweight champion. . . . U.S. Open champion Pete Sampras, suffering from
painful shin splints, pulled out of the Australian Open, which begins Monday.  </TEXT>
